Notes:
Dear Debbie,
I am so sorry that you lost your Dad this year.  He was such a beautiful person. Jerry and I both loved him so much – there wasn’t a soul on earth that he couldn’t connect with. 
I found after my sister Amy died and the flurry of activity slowed, that the grief settles in, and in the most unexpected moments. The loss crashes on you like a tsunami. It’s hard to feel like the same person because life actually is different without them. Life itself has changed. 
I’m so sorry you have to experience the pain of losing him. It’s heartbreaking. I can’t tell you that everything will be ok. I am so sorry that I cannot be there to simply hug you.
My sad but beautiful tradition was born over this last year when 2 separate friend’s lost their mothers; I take a clipping from my very favorite plant, and propagate it so that new life is born. My plant is a Monstera. Sadly I am not allowed to send my plant across the Canadian border but I am sending you a Monstera locally to nurture and love.  It grows up and out like a gorgeous jungle. I feel like it’s like a parent’s love; all encompassing, lush, complex, sometimes overbearing, endlessly giving and growing - wrapping roots around all those near and far with his large, loving, protective leaves, a nurturing life force from air and earth.
Your love and memories of him will always live on. I hope this little plant grows into the jungle of love your Dad held specifically for you. He is always with you; surrounding you, rooting you, and blossoming with you.

Love, Sara
